\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886\charrsid7161886 I.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886  GENERAL COMMENTS
\par 
\par 1. GENERAL STATE OF CONFIDENCE AND REACTION TO NEWS
\par 
\par In spite of "fresh Russian victories every day", and satisfaction with the renewal of the Allied air offensive, spirits are slightly lower this week. This is attributed to:
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid7161886 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 (a) "The tough going in Italy."
\par 
\par (b) Continued uneasiness about Allied co-operation with the Badoglio Government.
\par 
\par (c) The German recapture of Cos.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid7161886 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
\par Comment continues about strikes and the situation in the coal mining industry; also about post-war conditions - The "brave new world" is thought unlikely to materialise.
\par 
\par Several reports refer to fatigue, and people are said to be "far more edgy and snappy".
\par Footwear is again the main domestic complaint.
\par 
\par (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9.10.11.13.\tab 17.\tab 18 passim.)
\par 
\par 2. ITALY
\par 
\par Military: No one now expects the fighting to be easy: "As long as we\rquote re going upwards there, it's all to the good".
\par 
\par There is sympathy for what our men are undergoing, and among relatives - anxiety for them.
\par 
\par Political: Widespread dissatisfaction and uneasiness arc again reported over "our collaboration" with Badoglio's Government. There are frequent references to the pr
esent situation as a "repetition of the Darlan affair". That Roatta, Keitel's friend and persecutor of the Balkan peoples, should be in this Government is particularly mentioned.
\par 
\par Most people appear to dislike the idea of the Italians as Allies: "Have we t
o forget about their atrocities from now on?" It is felt we are being too kind to them, and feared that "other war-guilty culprits" in Hungary, Rumania and even Germany "will slip out of punishment, scot free".
\par 
\par Feeling is as hostile as over to Badoglio and King Victor Emmanuel.
\par 
\par A minority accept military necessity as an adequate reason for political collaboration with Badoglio (One Region).
\par 
\par German destruction in Italy continues to be deplored, though it is felt to be just what is expected of the Germans.
\par 
\par Anxiety for the fate of Rome and the Vatican is again reported among more thoughtful people. But there is also feeling that their damage by the Germans might do good by arousing stronger anti-German opinion among Roman Catholics everywhere; further, dama
ge by us might subsequently be necessary, as military considerations must come and these cities mustn't escape if the Germans
\par stay".
\par 
\par (1,2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.3.9.10.11.13.17.18 passim.)
\par 
\par 3. YUGOSLAV PATRIOTS
\par 
\par Admiration for them continues, as also does an uneasy feeling that we have let them down: "Why can't vie help them now?"
\par 
\par (2.4.5.7.8.11)
\par 
\par 4.  THE FALL OF COS
\par 
\par "Why take it, if we couldn't hold it?" is the dominant sentiment.
\par (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.9.10.11.13)
\par 
\par 5. RUSSIA
\par 
\par People were "simply amazed" at the news of fresh Russian assaults, as they had begun to accept the slowing of the Russian advance as a sign the autumn lull had come.
\par 
\par While some think that the Germans are withdrawing according to plan, the majority are sure these are real victories for the Russians and are full of admiration.
\par 
\par Speculation continues as to what will happen when the Russians reach their frontiers; workers "scoff at the idea" of them making a separate peace: "Nothing will stop them until they g
et into Germany and can give the Germans some of the treatment they have suffered at German hands." It is very much hoped that the Russians will got to Berlin first "as they would be less lenient than us in dealing with the enemy".
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid7161886 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 Conflicting feelings on familiar lines arc again reported about:
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid7161886 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid7161886 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
(a) British-U.S. aid to Russia. Some feel Russia has borne the brunt of the war so far and we should be doing more to help her. Others resent Russia's apparent lack of appreciation of what we have done and are doing.
\par 
\par (b) Russia's -say about peace terms. Some hope Russia will play a part in post-war Europe; a few of these suspect that the British and U.S. arc waiting for Russia to exhaust herself against Germany, so that when peace terms are dictated her hitting po
wer will be reduced. Others fear that Germany may collapse before our part in her defeat is as big as Russia's and that Russia will therefore be intractable about the peace terms.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid7161886 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
\par The Three Power Conference: People hope for good results: Better relations closer co-operation with Russia.
\par 
\par Stalingrad Sword: Bristol people are indignant that it is not \'85long to them - especially as they claim the highest contribution to aid id for Russia.
\par 
\par (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9.10.11.13. 17.\tab 18 passim.)
\par 
\par 6. ALLIED AIR OFFENSIVE
\par 
\par Great and widespread satisfaction is expressed with the renewal of our heavy raids on Germany (Ten Regions).
\par 
\par Criticism is chiefly on the lines that bombing must be even heavi
er, so that the Germans may pay fully for their misdeeds, It is felt that the promised "city by city bombing" has not yet been accomplished and that Berlin should be bombed more often and more heavily. Sleepless nights in Britain in 1940 are recalled, and
 it is suggested that raids of longer duration might lower German morale more effectively than "cascade" raids.
\par 
\par There is some anxiety over our casualties (Four Regions) as it is felt we are losing "the cream of our men".
\par 
\par The increase in the weight and number of U.S. raids is welcomed (Four Regions), though American claims of German aircraft destroyed on these raids are greeted with some cynicism (Four Regions).
\par 
\par (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9.10.11.13.\tab 18 passim.) 
\par 
\par 7. THE RAID ON LONDON, OCTOBER 7TH
\par 
\par Little comment has been reported outside London. Small reprisal or propaganda raids arc expected, but nothing more.
\par 
\par There are some complaints of the way the news was handled, early exaggerations led to "wild rumours".
\par 
\par In London a common feeling the following morning
 was that the raid was a magnificent sight, the danger of watching "adding zip and verve to the experience". Many people treated it as though it were a football match, "advice being shouted to both searchlight and gun crews". There is some criticism of th
is attitude, and suggestions that people should not be allowed to wander about the streets during raids, on account of the danger from falling A.A. shells.
\par 
\par There was a good deal of outspoken criticism of the\tab firing and the night fighters, for failing to de
al with enemy raiders, even when they were caught in searchlight beams. Press statements that shells apparently wide of the mark were in fact aimed at invisible planes are described as "stupid publicity". The bag of enemy raiders is regarded as poor.

\par 
\par (2.5.5SE.6.7.10)
\par 
\par 8. WAR AT SEA
\par 
\par There is sympathy for Sir Dudley Pound, and satisfaction at Sir Andrew Cunningham's appointment. .Sir Dudley Pound appears to have been looked on as an exponent of sound caution; Sir Andrew Cunningham is expected to be rather m
ore aggressive, in view of his Mediterranean exploits.
\par 
\par (1.2.3.5.7.9.13.18 twenty-one P.D.Rs.)
\par 
\par 9.\tab BENGAL FAMINE
\par 
\par The most general view is that we are to blame. Many \'85. Ignorance and ask for enlightenment. In Anglo-Indian centres, for example Chestenham, however, it is looked on as "a pooh introduction to any scheme of Government of India by the Indians".
\par 
\par (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.10. 17 Special P.C. 18 twenty P.D.Rs.)
\par 
\par 10.\tab THE NEXT MOVE
\par 
\par Discussion is again on a much reduced scale. Many feel it is too late in the year now for a major attack on Western Europe - it must wait till next spring. Some, however, expect a landing elsewhere, and the Balkans are favoured. Some think General Smuts' 
arrival in this country portends "a big new move".
\par 
\par (1.2.4.5.9.1O.13)
\par 
\par 11.\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6620336 THE FIVE AMERICAN SENATORS }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
\par 
\par Their remarks have aroused some anti-American feeling, but comment is not widespread.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid6620336 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 (3.5SE.6.11)
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid7161886 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
\par 12. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6620336 THE NATIONAL CONFERENCE OF WOMEN}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
\par 
\par Comment is on 
the same lines as last week, but tends to be more favourable. Some approve the principle of such contact between Government and people at intervals, and welcome a sign that the Government is recognising, the status of women in the war and the importance o
f the home front. It is thought to have been "a good thing\'94 to let the women got their grievances off their chest".
\par 
\par Others tend to regard the Conference as "a rather obvious means of bolstering up female morale".
\par 
\par Criticism continues on the lines of:
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid6620336 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 (a) "why the secrecy?" (Six Regions)
\par (b) "How were the delegates chosen?" (Five Regions) "Who invited them?" "What bodies were, or were not, represented?"
\par (c) Did it justify the expense and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6620336 the travel? (Two Regions each).
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid6620336 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6620336 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 (4.5.5SE.6.7.9.10)
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid7161886 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6620336 13. BROADCASTING AND PRESENTATION OF NEWS}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
\par 
\par News bulletins are described as dull at present, (Two Regions) and it is asked whether a more personal touch could not be introduced without endangering security, e.g. by naming of county regiments.
\par 
\par The Brains Tr
ust (Eight Regions): Its return is again welcomed, but the programme is criticised. Questions - and some answers - are considered frivolous, McCulloch is missed, and the introduction of visitors "with no particular qualifications", such as actresses, is t
hought to be a mistake. In one Region it is thought the programme has improved.
\par 
\par B.B.C.: The following are praised this week: L.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6620336  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 W.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6620336  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
Brockington's postscript, October 3 (Four Regions); Alistair Cooke's American...
\par 
\par Commentary, October 9. Major Lewis Hastings' War Commentary, October 7; the Radio Doctor, and "Marching On" (Two Regions each).
\par 
\par Praise of symphony and light music comes from two Regions and dislike of variety and dance bands from three others.
\par 
\par The voices of Maurice Shillington and John Wessel arc again criticised.
\par 
\par Industrial broadcasts: According to the report from Northern Ireland, the B.B.C. has been "loudly praised" for extending to that Region broadcasts from war factories. This "helps' to keep Ulster industry on the map".
\par 
\par (1.2.3.4.5.53E.6.7.8.9.1O.11.13)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6620336 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 II. SPECIAL COMMENTS
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6620336 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 MONTHLY REVIEW
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6620336 
\par 14. POST-WAR}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
\par 
\par During the past four weeks there has been a considerable increase of comment on post-war matters (All Regions). People's greatest anxiety appears to be what is going to happen to them after the war; "Get the war finished first" is now hardly heard.
\par 
\par Considerable suspicion, in some cases cynicism, exists as to the Government's intentions (Eleven Regions); frequent references are made to "l
ast time", and a recurrence of "our failure then" is feared. The "continued neglect" of the various reports especially the Beveridge Report - causes particular bitterness and mistrust.
\par 
\par It is felt both that the Government has failed to declare its and that
 where promises have been made, these arc insincere and unlikely to be fulfilled. The "unemployment bogey" is being increasingly discussed (Wine Regions). Older men, particularly, are fearful as to what their position will be when young men are released f
rom the Forces and from the factories. The position of women is also discussed. In the shipyards and coalfields, and in the stool and cotton industries, particularly, there is said to be much fear of a slump similar to that which followed the last war.

\par 
\par The following post-war problems are also major subjects of discussion:
\par 
\par Housing: Much anxiety is felt about the housing position after the war (Seven Regions, most more than once). The position even now is felt to be acute, and an even worse shortage than aft
er the last war is feared. Not only planning but rebuilding, it is felt, should have been begun by now, and comparisons are made with press statements that the Russians have begun re-building. Excessive prices are also feared.
\par 
\par Education: The White Paper c
ontinues to be discussed (Nine Regions, several more than once), though chiefly among more thoughtful people. Most people want to sec a "rapid improvement in education" out there are some doubts as to whether we shall be able to afford it, and some fear t
hat religious differences will be allowed to stand in the way.
\par 
\par Agriculture: Farmers are anxious to hear of a definite policy for agriculture (Six Regions), and complain so far given no indication of its policy. They fear that once foreign and colonial mark
ets are opened again and shipping made available, a drift back to pre-war conditions will take place.
\par 
\par Post-war international relations (Seven Regions): There is said to be increasing awareness of the possibility of post-war difficulties in the internation
al sphere, and a growing fear that "the end of war will not mean the end of strife". Fears chiefly concern Russia the on the one hand, it is felt that we "may not be as eager to be friendly with Russia as we might"; on the other, that we shall be dominate
d by the US. 
\par 
\par Concerns as to our post-war attitude to the freed countries and to our ex-enemies has also been reported. (See sections on I Russia, and the Balkans in recent Home Intelligence Weekly Reports.)
\par 
\par Demobilisation:\tab 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid6620336 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 (a)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6620336  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 Bevin's speech at the Tra
des Union Congress. During the last three weeks there has continued to be a good deal of comment on Mr. Bevin's speech (Nine Regions). The majority appear to favour the idea of "First in, First out" as being "very fair\'94
, but there have been some criticisms
. Even among those in favour, there is some feeling that it is "fair but not practical", "It has a fine ring about it, but Mr. Bevin will find it difficult to put his slogan into practice without enough exceptions make it meaningless". The chief exception
s, it is though must be:
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid7161886 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li851\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin851\itap0\pararsid6620336 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 (i) "Key" men - so as to make work for the others (Four Regions),
\par 
\par (ii) Older men (Two Regions). "As it stands, men with the greatest responsibilities would be retained, since they were the last to be called up".
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid7161886 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li284\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin284\itap0\pararsid6620336 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 (b) The "points" 
scheme for demobilisation has aroused some favourable comment this week (Six Regions). It is described as a "fair and conciliatory" arrangement.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid7161886 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
\par Mr. Morrison on the need for post-war controls:  Comment has been mixed (Nine Regions. The general attitude ap
pears to be that while the necessity for continued controls after the war is recognised, "they must go at the earliest possible moment". For most pool: controls appear to be equivalent to the restrictions which them personally.
\par 
\par Some curiosity is reported as to whether Mr. Morrison\rquote s views represent those of the Government (Three Regions).
\par 
