\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6620336 15. INDUSTRY}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
\par 
\par Strikes continue to cause much discussion, but it appears to be slightly less in extent and intensity than last week, though e almost exactly the same lines (see. Home Intelligence Report, No. 157 Section 14).
\par 
\par The Barrow strike: There is relief that this has been settled "after dragging on too long". Some are surprised at the aware they feel that 
"the Barrow men got what they wanted" and wonder if the employers were in the wrong all the time. There is a feeling that \'85
en must have had some real cause for dissatisfaction, or they would not have taken up such a firm stand. "The dark days when Barrow was one of our worst depressed areas have not been entirely forgotten.
\par 
\par As with all strikes, however, the majority feeling is that strike action in wartime is unjustified.
\par 
\par The causes of industrial unrest and strikes: People continue to seek for causes unde
rlying the surface motives. Fatigue and war-weariness, combined with the belief that we are "out of the wood" and victory now certain, arc thought by many to account for the situation. Uneasiness about the Government's attitude to post-war conditions is q
uoted to a less extent. Some continue to suspect agitators and subversive activities.
\par 
\par During the past four weeks most industrial comment has been on strikes and the supposed reasons for them, but there has been some talk about:
\par 
\par Enforced idleness in factories (See Constant Topics, No.8). Comment is on familiar lines, e.g. of "a woman who earns \'a3
4 a week doing nothing but knitting". Particular mention is made of Metropolitan Vickers (North Western Region) and Standard Telephone and Cables, New Southgate (London Region).
\par 
\par Transfer of workers (Six Regions). The main complaint has been of transfer to loss well paid jobs, but there have again been allegations of unnecessary transfer, and of inadequate accommodation for transferred workers.
\par 
\par (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9.10.11.\tab 17 five provincial P.Cs.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6620336  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 18 passim.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6620336 16. MINERS AND MINING}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
\par 
\par The mining situation is still causing much concern. People feel that "none of the measures so far taken or contemplated will suffice", and that the whole problem should be the subject of 
special inquiry. While some think firm action should be taken with the miners, others, remembering their past history, are sympathetic. In the Northern Region some miners think that the position of the industry to-day is "worse than it has ever been in li
v
ing memory", owing to the lack of new-comers; they say that much of the trouble is due to the elder average age of the present-day miner who "cannot keep the pace up". They also say "there is no security, and the co-operation between owners and workmen is
 practically nil".
\par  
\par There is little comment on the proposals of the Miners' Federation. Some say "increased wages, which seems to be their main proposal, will not lead to greater production, probably the reverse", while others feel that wages are too low a
nd the "request for \'a3
6 a week should be granted". Some minors feel there should be a substantial difference between wages of surface and underground workers, and again, between those of men at the coal face and underground haulage workers. Also that piece 
rates which are "still on the 1931 basis" should be increased. 
\par 
\par Man-power in mines: There is again a) Belief that skilled men should be withdrawn from the Forces (Five Regions); (b) Scepticism about the success of the appeal for volunteers (Two Regions); 
(c) Objection to the direction of youths into pits, and fears of discrimination... Battle of Waterloo was won on the playing fields of Eton; the battle for coal should be won on the same ground."
\par 
\par Absenteeism: Scottish miners' loaders believe there has been unfair discrimination in the Courts and they are bringing this to the notice of Lord Traprain.
\par 
\par One Regional report states that it is thought there would be less absenteeism if miners were allowed Saturday off for recreation. The recent suggestion for in
creasing output by working an extra shift on Saturday and one Sunday a month is not approved, as "it could only result in still further reduction owing to the exhausting nature of the work".
\par 
\par (1.3.4.5.8.9.11.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6620336  17. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 18 five P.D.Rs.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6620336 17. DOMESTIC FUEL}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
\par 
\par During
 the past four weeks complaints of the difficulty of getting fuel for storage, or even for immediate use, have been reported from eight Regions...."One bag every three weeks" is reported from Wigtownshire. In the circumstances, people are said to find the
 
"store fuel now" advertisements "rather irritating", and there is uneasiness about a possible shortage during the coming winter (Six Regions). In Scotland, it is said that difficulty of transport prevents people from storing wood blocks, of which there is
 \'93an abundance at forestry camps".
\par 
\par Less is heard of the need to save fuel (Four Regions)..."People are less disposed to do without fires this year, on the grounds that so many succumbed to illness last year which they blamed on lack of heating."
\par 
\par There is some criticism of the quality of coal supplied for household use (Two Regions) , and it is suggested that inferior coal should be controlled at graded prices.
\par 
\par The ban on central heating is causing complaint now that the weather is colder (Six Regions). In
 many offices in Scotland it is being defied: but, where strictly enforced, "conditions are extremely unpleasant and a crop of influenza colds and sore throats is already apparent".
\par 
\par (2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9.10.11.\tab 18 five P.D.Rs.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6620336 18. MAN-POWER}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
\par 
\par The registra
tion of older women: Comment continues on familiar lines (See Constant Topics, No.2a) but fooling appears to be less intense. In working-class areas where "it is quite normal for women to be working up to the age of 70", the outcry is said to be regarded 
with bitter amusement and as "one of the most blatant expressions of class differences". The prospect of being called up is said to have produced a new crop of landladies in billeting areas where two war workers as lodgers procure exemption.
\par 
\par During the pas
t four weeks the main man-power topic has been / the registration of older women, which in turn has stimulated allegations of overstaffing and the need for a comb-out of younger women in the Women's and Civil Services, etc. (See Constant Topics, No.2b). P
a
rticular establishments which are thought to be overstaffed are "the Barrow Iron and Steel Works, which the Ministry of Supply is alleged to have overstaffed with girl clerks"; the Admiralty near Haslemere; the Royal Naval armament Depot near Fishguard; t
he Ministry of Aircraft Production at Oakwood Court, Kensington.
\par 
\par Throughout this period there have been repeated references - mostly unspecified - to a feeling that man-power is not being used to the best advantage (Seven Regions).
\par 
\par Some references have also been made to:
\par 
\par The difficulties of small businesses as the result of the call-up (Three Regions). Small traders and those employing a small amount of labour feel aggrieved about individual cases of call-up where it is suggested th
at hardship exists and is ignored, or whore special training or aptitude is thought to be ruthlessly wasted. Some small manufacturers feel "they are being pushed out by the National Service Officer to the advantage of bigger concerns".
\par 
\par (1,2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6620336 ,3,4,5,5SE,6,7,8,9,10,11,13,17 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 four provincial P. Cs. 18 four P.D.Rs.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6620336 19}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 . }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6620336 HOUSING AND BILLETING }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
\par 
\par During the past four weeks complaints of the shortage of housing accommodation have been widespread (Ten Regions). 'Newlyweds unable to make homos of their own, and mother
s with small children "who are not welcome in other people's houses" suffer especially. Conditions are said to be particularly bad in London and it is asked "whether it is absolutely impossible to build some houses in the London area".
\par 
\par Property being in bad repair is also complained of: "there is an endless tale of leaking roofs, damp walls and unglazed windows". The "apparent apathy of the responsible authorities" is deplored.
\par 
\par There are also complaints of excessive rents both for furnished and unfurnished accommodation.
\par 
\par Local Authorities' powers to requisition empty houses (Three Regions): It is complained that the Government have only "given powers to" and not "obliged" Local Authorities to requisition property, and that too many loop-holes have been le
ft.  Dissatisfaction, it is thought, will be widespread, if the new powers prove a "dead letter". In the East End of London there has been a "stream of enquiries" and much annoyance when it is found that "little or nothing can be done".
\par 
\par Agricultural housing:  Sarcastic comment continues regarding the new cottages (Five Regions). They are said to have tiny windows, stone floors, and "hot pipes running through the larder"..." At \'a3
950 they are just laughed at". A "speedy improvement in housing conditions for farm workers\'94 is thought to be needed, but the cottages are considered a. poor omen for the future.
\par 
\par Billeting: There are complaints of difficulties experienced by transferred workers in finding suitable accommodation and of their "exploitation" by landladies (Three Regions).
\par 
\par Compulsory billeting "when so many large houses and halls stand empty" is also complained of (Three Regions). The allowance for billetees is considered inadequate. American troops are referred to - eightpence a night "doesn't cover th
e cost of laundry, heating and lighting those days". 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6620336 (2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9.10.13. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 17)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6620336 20. CLOTHING}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
\par 
\par During the past four' weeks clothing difficulties have remained a major topic of discussion. Complaints are chiefly:
\par 
\par Footwear difficulties (All Regions). It is feared that much sickness particularly among children, will result this winter from faulty footwear. The difficulty of keeping children equipped with shoes is said to be the housewives' foremost difficulty. Compl
aints are chiefly of:
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid6620336 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
(a) The poor quality of shoes (Twelve Regions). Children' a shoes, particularly, are said to last only a fortnight or three weeks, and mothers have "neither the money nor the coupons to make the Accessary replacements". Some shoes are
 said to be so shoddy that they cannot be repaired.
\par 
\par The promise that better shoes will be provided for children has been welcomed, but "about time too".
\par 
\par (b) The difficulty of getting shoos repaired (Ten Regions). The length of time they are kept, the poo
r leather used, in some cases the difficulty of getting repairs undertaken, make the footwear problem "almost insuperable". The difficulty of obtaining leather for home repairs adds to the problem.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid7161886 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
\par The inadequacy of clothing coupons is another major topic
 (all Regions). The present number is thought "wholly insufficient" to obtain essential clothing, especially during the winter months when warm underclothes are required. Most people either had no reserves of clothing or else have now exhausted them.

\par 
\par Household coupons: The demand for household coupons continue& (Eleven Regions). Coupons are thought inadequate for personal clothing, without "sacrifices" having to be made by the housewife.
\par 
\par Coupons for industrial workers (Nine Regions). Various classes of wo
rkers - including miners and farm labourers, chemical and steel workers, Civil Defence and transport personnel - are "frantic" because they "cannot keep pace with the speed at which their clothes wear out". Those who get no extra allowance of coupons are 
said to be growing increasingly bitter.
\par 
\par There are also complaints of the   inadequacy of coupons for growing children (Seven Regions) and for expectant mothers (Two Regions).
\par 
\par Women's stockings. Those are now a "real topic" (Seven Regions). "The poor quality" of utility stockings, their "drabness" and "clumsiness" are particularly deplored.
\par 
\par Interest in the new utility stockings is "balked by their non-availability" (South-Western Region).
\par 
\par Ther}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9110651 e are again allegations of the p}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 oor quality of utility clothes. Gene}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9110651 rally (Six Regions) and of the}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886  false economy in their cut (Two Regions).
\par 
\par Laundry: difficulties (Three Regions). There are complaints of the "wear and tear" at laundries. "Now that the average housewife has to go out to work, clothes, are wearing out doubly quickly owing to ruination at laundries."
\par 
\par (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.9.10.11.13.\tab 17 passim.18. 20 P.D.Rs.)
\par 
\par 
\par During the past four weeks there have been complaints of:
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid6620336 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6620336  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
(a) High wages, particularly of juveniles but also of munition workers, labourers on aerodrome sites and unskilled workers generally. Agricultural labourers' wages are mentioned in three reports, according to one of which "their continued rise is causing 
c
onsiderable anxiety to small farmers: some are finding it difficult to pay these high wages, and a good many of them are worse off than their employees". The Eastern Region report also refers to the rising and competitive prices for seasonal agricultural 
labour, such as potato pulling and beet cutting which may be as high, oven for a child, as \'a35 or \'a36 a week; some think the price of such labour should be controlled.
\par 
\par (b) Disparity in pay, particularly between unskilled or semiskilled workers and:
