\par 22. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8939194 "PAY-AS-YOU-EARN\'94 INCOME TAX}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
\par 
\par Further expressions of approval, particularly by workers: "From what I read
, Kingsley Wood seems to have departed this life leaving behind a grand memorial". Some however, are waiting to see how it works, before expressing approval. The need for a clear explanation of the scheme is again stressed: "The statement that it can be c
arried out quite simply by employers of labour is regarded with suspicion and more information is asked for" (One region).
\par 
\par Disappointment and criticism continue at:
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid8939194 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
(a) The exclusion of those paid on a monthly basis (Eight Regions). This is described as "
manifestly unfair to the black coats", and it is suggested that no one should be excluded from the scheme who receives less than the highest paid weekly worker. One suggested inequality is that in hospitals, male nurses who are paid weekly will be include
d in the scheme, but women nurses-, receiving less money but paid monthly, will not 'benefit.
\par 
\par (b) The writing off of arrears (Two Regions). Though "a tonic" to those who benefit, this is resented by some of those who do not. The black coat worker considers
 he will be "shouldering the millions which the Chancellor's munificence is relieving, the manual worker of paying". People are said to be getting tired of "this discrimination in favour of the manual worker".
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid7161886 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
