\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8939194 23. TRANSPORT DIFFICULTIES}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
\par 
\par Transport difficulties have continued to be a widespread tonic during the last four weeks. A slight increase in difficulties. has latterly been reported from London and the South Western Regions.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid8939194 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 (a) Overcrowding of buses and t
rains (Eight Regions, several more than once) by (i) short distance travelers-crowding out long distance travelers (Four Regions); (ii) shoppers and pleasure seekers Two Regions); (iii) school children (Two Regions).
\par 
\par (b) Inadequacy of rural transport (Seven Regions, several more than once) Particular mention is made of the difficulty of women in outlying districts getting into towns to do their shopping before the shops are sold out.
\par 
\par (c) The restriction of evening and Sunday morning buses (Five Regions): 
Workers would like later evening services to enable them to visit cinemas and theatres. In the Eastern Region the suspension of Sunday morning buses is giving hardship to villagers wishing to visit relatives in hospital.
\par 
\par (d) Queues for buses (Three Regions): Long waits in Queues for buses in the cold weather arc a source of irritation.
\par 
\par (c) Inadequacy of bus services at peak periods (Two Regions).
\par 
\par (f) The failure of buses the stop and pick up passengers in the blackout (Two Regions).
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid7161886 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
