\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8939194 26. SHOPPING DIFFICULTIES AND FOOD QUEUES}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
\par 
\par During the past four weeks complaints have been rather less but they follow familiar lines:
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid8939194 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 
(a) Queues (Seven Regions). War workers and housewives alike complain of time wasted in queues. Many blame bad distribution to retailers for the trouble; others say "some people make an occupation of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8939194 queuing}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7161886 ".
\par 
\par (b) Lunchtime and the earlier winter closing of shops (Six Regions). Workers have great difficulty in getting foodstuffs and goods; on the quota system wh
ich are sold out early in the day. Some feel that where there is More than one assistant, shops should remain open during the lunch hour. The earlier winter closing is "dreaded as this makes matters worse".
\par 
\par (c) Country bus restrictions (Five Regions). Vil
lagers have difficulty in getting to neighbouring towns before the shops are sold out of "extras and pointed goods", and they feel there should be some system whereby they get a fair share. In the South Western Region the "special weekly bus for villagers
 to shop in Bristol is a real boon".
